README.md
     1‚Üí# color [![](https://github.com/fatih/color/workflows/build/badge.svg)](https://github.com/fatih/color/actions) [![PkgGoDev](https://pkg.go.dev/badge/github.com/fatih/color)](https://pkg.go.dev/github.com/fatih/color)
     2‚Üí
     3‚ÜíColor lets you use colorized outputs in terms of [ANSI Escape
     4‚ÜíCodes](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ANSI_escape_code#Colors) in Go (Golang). It
     5‚Üíhas support for Windows too! The API can be used in several ways, pick one that
     6‚Üísuits you.
     7‚Üí
     8‚Üí![Color](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/438920/96832689-03b3e000-13f4-11eb-9803-46f4c4de3406.jpg)
     9‚Üí
    10‚Üí## Install
    11‚Üí
    12‚Üí```
    13‚Üígo get github.com/fatih/color
    14‚Üí```
    15‚Üí
    16‚Üí## Examples
    17‚Üí
    18‚Üí### Standard colors
    19‚Üí
    20‚Üí```go
    21‚Üí// Print with default helper functions
    22‚Üícolor.Cyan("Prints text in cyan.")
    23‚Üí
    24‚Üí// A newline will be appended automatically
    25‚Üícolor.Blue("Prints %s in blue.", "text")
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí// These are using the default foreground colors
    28‚Üícolor.Red("We have red")
    29‚Üícolor.Magenta("And many others ..")
    30‚Üí
    31‚Üí```
    32‚Üí
    33‚Üí### RGB colors
    34‚Üí
    35‚ÜíIf your terminal supports 24-bit colors, you can use RGB color codes.
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí```go
    38‚Üícolor.RGB(255, 128, 0).Println("foreground orange")
    39‚Üícolor.RGB(230, 42, 42).Println("foreground red")
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üícolor.BgRGB(255, 128, 0).Println("background orange")
    42‚Üícolor.BgRGB(230, 42, 42).Println("background red")
    43‚Üí```
    44‚Üí
    45‚Üí### Mix and reuse colors
    46‚Üí
    47‚Üí```go
    48‚Üí// Create a new color object
    49‚Üíc := color.New(color.FgCyan).Add(color.Underline)
    50‚Üíc.Println("Prints cyan text with an underline.")
    51‚Üí
    52‚Üí// Or just add them to New()
    53‚Üíd := color.New(color.FgCyan, color.Bold)
    54‚Üíd.Printf("This prints bold cyan %s\n", "too!.")
    55‚Üí
    56‚Üí// Mix up foreground and background colors, create new mixes!
    57‚Üíred := color.New(color.FgRed)
    58‚Üí
    59‚ÜíboldRed := red.Add(color.Bold)
    60‚ÜíboldRed.Println("This will print text in bold red.")
    61‚Üí
    62‚ÜíwhiteBackground := red.Add(color.BgWhite)
    63‚ÜíwhiteBackground.Println("Red text with white background.")
    64‚Üí
    65‚Üí// Mix with RGB color codes
    66‚Üícolor.RGB(255, 128, 0).AddBgRGB(0, 0, 0).Println("orange with black background")
    67‚Üí
    68‚Üícolor.BgRGB(255, 128, 0).AddRGB(255, 255, 255).Println("orange background with white foreground")
    69‚Üí```
    70‚Üí
    71‚Üí### Use your own output (io.Writer)
    72‚Üí
    73‚Üí```go
    74‚Üí// Use your own io.Writer output
    75‚Üícolor.New(color.FgBlue).Fprintln(myWriter, "blue color!")
    76‚Üí
    77‚Üíblue := color.New(color.FgBlue)
    78‚Üíblue.Fprint(writer, "This will print text in blue.")
    79‚Üí```
    80‚Üí
    81‚Üí### Custom print functions (PrintFunc)
    82‚Üí
    83‚Üí```go
    84‚Üí// Create a custom print function for convenience
    85‚Üíred := color.New(color.FgRed).PrintfFunc()
    86‚Üíred("Warning")
    87‚Üíred("Error: %s", err)
    88‚Üí
    89‚Üí// Mix up multiple attributes
    90‚Üínotice := color.New(color.Bold, color.FgGreen).PrintlnFunc()
    91‚Üínotice("Don't forget this...")
    92‚Üí```
    93‚Üí
    94‚Üí### Custom fprint functions (FprintFunc)
    95‚Üí
    96‚Üí```go
    97‚Üíblue := color.New(color.FgBlue).FprintfFunc()
    98‚Üíblue(myWriter, "important notice: %s", stars)
    99‚Üí
   100‚Üí// Mix up with multiple attributes
   101‚Üísuccess := color.New(color.Bold, color.FgGreen).FprintlnFunc()
   102‚Üísuccess(myWriter, "Don't forget this...")
   103‚Üí```
   104‚Üí
   105‚Üí### Insert into noncolor strings (SprintFunc)
   106‚Üí
   107‚Üí```go
   108‚Üí// Create SprintXxx functions to mix strings with other non-colorized strings:
   109‚Üíyellow := color.New(color.FgYellow).SprintFunc()
   110‚Üíred := color.New(color.FgRed).SprintFunc()
   111‚Üífmt.Printf("This is a %s and this is %s.\n", yellow("warning"), red("error"))
   112‚Üí
   113‚Üíinfo := color.New(color.FgWhite, color.BgGreen).SprintFunc()
   114‚Üífmt.Printf("This %s rocks!\n", info("package"))
   115‚Üí
   116‚Üí// Use helper functions
   117‚Üífmt.Println("This", color.RedString("warning"), "should be not neglected.")
   118‚Üífmt.Printf("%v %v\n", color.GreenString("Info:"), "an important message.")
   119‚Üí
   120‚Üí// Windows supported too! Just don't forget to change the output to color.Output
   121‚Üífmt.Fprintf(color.Output, "Windows support: %s", color.GreenString("PASS"))
   122‚Üí```
   123‚Üí
   124‚Üí### Plug into existing code
   125‚Üí
   126‚Üí```go
   127‚Üí// Use handy standard colors
   128‚Üícolor.Set(color.FgYellow)
   129‚Üí
   130‚Üífmt.Println("Existing text will now be in yellow")
   131‚Üífmt.Printf("This one %s\n", "too")
   132‚Üí
   133‚Üícolor.Unset() // Don't forget to unset
   134‚Üí
   135‚Üí// You can mix up parameters
   136‚Üícolor.Set(color.FgMagenta, color.Bold)
   137‚Üídefer color.Unset() // Use it in your function
   138‚Üí
   139‚Üífmt.Println("All text will now be bold magenta.")
   140‚Üí```
   141‚Üí
   142‚Üí### Disable/Enable color
   143‚Üí
   144‚ÜíThere might be a case where you want to explicitly disable/enable color output. the 
   145‚Üí`go-isatty` package will automatically disable color output for non-tty output streams 
   146‚Üí(for example if the output were piped directly to `less`).
   147‚Üí
   148‚ÜíThe `color` package also disables color output if the [`NO_COLOR`](https://no-color.org) environment
   149‚Üívariable is set to a non-empty string.
   150‚Üí
   151‚Üí`Color` has support to disable/enable colors programmatically both globally and
   152‚Üífor single color definitions. For example suppose you have a CLI app and a
   153‚Üí`-no-color` bool flag. You can easily disable the color output with:
   154‚Üí
   155‚Üí```go
   156‚Üívar flagNoColor = flag.Bool("no-color", false, "Disable color output")
   157‚Üí
   158‚Üíif *flagNoColor {
   159‚Üí	color.NoColor = true // disables colorized output
   160‚Üí}
   161‚Üí```
   162‚Üí
   163‚ÜíIt also has support for single color definitions (local). You can
   164‚Üídisable/enable color output on the fly:
   165‚Üí
   166‚Üí```go
   167‚Üíc := color.New(color.FgCyan)
   168‚Üíc.Println("Prints cyan text")
   169‚Üí
   170‚Üíc.DisableColor()
   171‚Üíc.Println("This is printed without any color")
   172‚Üí
   173‚Üíc.EnableColor()
   174‚Üíc.Println("This prints again cyan...")
   175‚Üí```
   176‚Üí
   177‚Üí## GitHub Actions
   178‚Üí
   179‚ÜíTo output color in GitHub Actions (or other CI systems that support ANSI colors), make sure to set `color.NoColor = false` so that it bypasses the check for non-tty output streams. 
   180‚Üí
   181‚Üí
